messages.text: I am now 9,000 miles from the surface of Pluto.
Excellent. Inform us immediately if you see anything unusual.
By the way, is my wife on the line?
How does it look up there?
Stark and lonely. But it's beautiful.
Loss of contact begins in t-minus 60 seconds.
When will I hear from you again, Martin?
I'll be back in contact in 22 hours.
I'll have man's first photos and measurements of Pluto by then :)
I’m proud of you, Martin. I love you.
Contact with Discovery has been lost.
We will regain contact in t-minus 22 hours.
But I didn't get to say goodbye!
Discovery should be entering the shadow of Charon, Pluto’s largest moon, right now.
In the evening, when Daniella is back home, her laptop lights up.
There is a dark expanse around its equator.
It's only been 11 hours. How are you contacting me??
I can confirm that Pluto has no fifth moon.
Are you in contact with NASA?
I’m looking at the photo I brought.
Of Christopher squeezing his little red ball.
And Martin, he loved you very much.
The disease took him from us too soon.
What do you mean? Is everything okay?
There is something here. It is reaching for me.
We are sorry to tell you that we’ve lost all traces of Discovery.
But Martin was just in contact with me less than a minute ago!
We have no evidence of recent contact.
I just heard his voice over the radio!
Ask him to send us his vital signs.
Martin, are you there? Answer me.
Honey, you need to send your vital signs to the NASA doctors.
Can you hear what he’s saying?
Tell him to send his pulse.
Please send them your vital signs now!
You’re not on their systems, baby.
Do you see? Do you see?
I’m going to be with him now.
With who, Martin? You’re up there alone.
That doesn’t sound like you, Martin!
A message appears on Daniella’s laptop.
Are you currently in contact with Martin, Daniella?
But he doesn’t sound like himself at all.
We have no oxygen readings, Daniella.
All life-sustaining systems have shut down.
Oh god no. How long does he have?
We have critical shutdown on all systems.
In her despair, Daniella messages her husband.
Two weeks later, Daniella receives a text from NASA.
We have confirmation from the radio dish in California that Discovery is on a trajectory for the Baltic Sea.
We will notify you when we have opened the spacecraft.
You will be able to view the remains in private.
One minute later, Daniella’s laptop lights up.
They are about to take me.
I have someone here who wants to talk to you.
Christopher, say hello to your mother.
I was so sick in the hospital.
And now Daddy is here too.
Christopher? Could that really be you?
We are sending something down to you as a sign.
Daniella, we can see Discovery on radar.
The Hubbell Telescope confirms visual that Discovery is re-entering our atmosphere.
Teams are stationed around the craft.
We have breached the seal and are inside Discovery.
This is baffling. No one is here.
There is no trace of Martin or his remains.
There is no evidence that Martin was ever here.
We did find a red ball.
You mean a photo of our son holding a red ball?
No — not a photo. An actual red ball.
But Martin didn’t take a red ball with him into space.
We haven’t seen that ball since our child was buried with it.
That must have been the sign.
They said they would send a sign.
It’s a sign that my husband and son are out there.
And that other life is out there too.
Request has been granted to send a probe to investigate astronaut Martin Hale’s mysterious disappearance.
And to commence a search for alien life.
